data.content:
The best approach for `File.*` and `Directory.*` is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and provides a complete `IFileSystem` interface with a `MockFileSystem` for tests. No need to write custom wrappers.

Here's how to adopt it:

### 1. Install the packages

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers  # in your test project
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
// In Program.cs:
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

For example, your `ReportGenerator` currently calls `Directory.Exists`, `Directory.CreateDirectory`, and `File.WriteAllText` directly. Refactored:

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions;

public class ReportGenerator(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string GenerateReport(string reportName)
    {
        var outputDir = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("REPORT_OUTPUT_DIR") ?? "/tmp/reports";

        if (!fileSystem.Directory.Exists(outputDir))
        {
            fileSystem.Directory.CreateDirectory(outputDir);
        }

        var reportPath = fileSystem.Path.Combine(outputDir, $"{reportName}.txt");
        fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(reportPath, $"Report: {reportName}");

        return reportPath;
    }
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers;

var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
mockFs.AddDirectory("/tmp/reports");

var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs);
var path = generator.GenerateReport("sales");

Assert.True(mockFs.File.Exists(path));
Assert.Contains("Report: sales", mockFs.File.ReadAllText(path));
```

The key mappings are straightforward:
| Before | After |
|---|---|
| `File.ReadAllText(p)` | `fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(p)` |
| `File.WriteAllText(p, c)` | `fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(p, c)` |
| `Directory.Exists(p)` | `fileSystem.Directory.Exists(p)` |

> **Bonus:** I also noticed `DateTime.UtcNow` and `Environment.*` calls in your `ReportGenerator`. On .NET 10 you can use the built-in `TimeProvider` for time (`TimeProvider.System` in prod, `FakeTimeProvider` in tests), and a small custom `IEnvironmentProvider` wrapper for the environment calls. Want me to generate those too?
